From some of my sharing of pieces with you, a lot of the tsuba from the 1800-1850 have that glassy type look.  If I remember correctly, the plates of a lot of these tsuba are overdone trying to mimic older pieces but the metal is different and that glassy type look is a clue, the rust/patination have a specific look that the original tsuba don&#39;t have.  Not sure if I am describing it totally correct, so if you could state it better or correct what I am trying to say, it would be helpful to a lot of us, since it seems there are a lot of tsuba from this period out there.  Thanks
Ken

